Internal parametric likelihood-ratio helpers

Developer-facing documentation for the helpers that implement the parametric
Bernoulli-plus-Normal likelihood-ratio path used by \code{method = "LRT"}.
\subsection{\code{parametric_safe_xlogy(x, y)}}{

Computes \code{x * log(y)} elementwise while forcing structurally zero terms to
remain zero. \code{x} and \code{y} are numeric vectors, and the helper returns a numeric
vector of the same length. It avoids evaluating \code{log(0)} for cells where
\code{x == 0}. Its role is to support exact Bernoulli fallback likelihoods at the
observation-probability boundaries.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_odds_ratio(pi1, pi0)}}{

Converts two observation probabilities into the treatment-versus-control odds
ratio. \code{pi1} and \code{pi0} are scalar probabilities. The helper returns a scalar
numeric value, including exact \code{0}, \code{1}, or \code{Inf} in the saturated boundary
cases. Its role is to preserve intuitive odds-ratio output when the logistic
model fit is not regular enough for Wald intervals.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_wald_interval(estimate, se, conf.level)}}{

Builds a symmetric Wald interval from a point estimate and standard error.
The helper returns a length-two numeric vector. It returns \code{c(NA, NA)} when
the standard error is missing, non-finite, or negative. Its role is to keep
interval generation consistent across the logistic and linear components.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_loglik_bernoulli(k, n, p)}}{

Evaluates the Bernoulli log-likelihood for \code{k} successes in \code{n} trials at
probability \code{p}. The helper returns a scalar numeric log-likelihood and is
used only in fallback calculations. Because it delegates the problematic terms
to \code{parametric_safe_xlogy()}, it remains defined at exact \code{0} and \code{1}
probabilities. Its role is to support boundary-stable likelihood-ratio
statistics when \code{glm()} is not trustworthy.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_model_formulas(adjust = NULL)}}{

Constructs the four regression formulas needed by the parametric path.
\code{adjust} is either \code{NULL} or a validated one-sided additive adjustment
formula. The helper returns a named list containing Bernoulli null and
alternative formulas plus Normal null and alternative formulas. When
adjustment is present, treatment \code{R} is added only to the alternatives. Its
role is to keep the conditional model specification synchronized across both
submodels.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_fit_glm(formula, data)} and \code{parametric_fit_lm(formula, data)}}{

Thin wrappers around \code{glm()} and \code{lm()} that suppress warnings and convert fit
failures to \code{NULL}. Their arguments are the model \code{formula} and the analysis
\code{data} frame. Each helper returns either the fitted model object or \code{NULL}.
Their role is to let later regularity checks decide whether a fit is usable
without immediately aborting the full \code{LRT} pipeline.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_fit_models(data, adjust = NULL)}}{

Fits the full set of logistic and linear models used by the parametric
likelihood-ratio calculation. \code{data} is the standardized analysis frame, and
\code{adjust} is the optional additive baseline-covariate formula. The helper
returns a list containing the model formulas, the Bernoulli fits, the
observed-outcome data subset, and the Normal fits. It quietly carries through
\code{NULL} fits from the lower-level wrappers. Its role is to provide a single
cacheable bundle for all downstream summaries.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_loglik_value(fit, reml = NULL)}}{

Extracts a scalar numeric log-likelihood from a fitted model. \code{fit} may be a
\code{glm}, \code{lm}, or \code{NULL}, and \code{reml} controls whether \code{lm} log-likelihoods are
requested with \code{REML = FALSE}. The helper returns \code{NA_real_} when extraction
fails. Its role is to isolate the fragile \code{logLik()} calls used throughout
the parametric path.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_clamp_statistic(statistic, tol = 1e-12)}}{

Forces very small finite negative likelihood-ratio values back to zero.
\code{statistic} is a scalar numeric candidate and \code{tol} is the non-negativity
tolerance. The helper returns the adjusted scalar. It leaves large negative
or non-finite values untouched so callers can still detect genuine problems.
Its role is to clean up roundoff artifacts after log-likelihood subtraction.
}

\subsection{\code{parametric_term_variance(fit, term)} and}{

\code{parametric_term_estimate(fit, term)}

Extract the variance or coefficient estimate for a named model term. \code{fit} is
a regression object and \code{term} is the coefficient name, typically \code{"R"}. Each
